  "prompt": "How does specific heat and heat capacity differ?",
  "response": "While both specific heat and heat capacity relate to the amount of heat required to change the temperature of a substance, they differ in what they refer to:\n\n**Heat Capacity (C)**\n\n*   **Definition:** The amount of heat energy required to raise the temperature of a *given amount* (mass) of a substance by 1 degree Celsius (or 1 Kelvin).\n*   **Units:** Typically expressed in Joules per degree Celsius (J/\u00b0C) or Joules per Kelvin (J/K). Sometimes also expressed in calories/\u00b0C or BTU/\u00b0F.\n*   **Dependency:**  Heat capacity is **extensive**, meaning it **depends on the amount of substance**. A larger mass will have a larger heat capacity because it will take more energy to raise the temperature of more material.\n*   **Formula:** C = Q / \u0394T, where:\n    *   C = Heat Capacity\n    *   Q = Heat Added or Removed\n    *   \u0394T = Change in Temperature\n\n**Specific Heat (c)**\n\n*   **Definition:**  The amount of heat energy required to raise the temperature of *1 gram* (or 1 kilogram, depending on the units) of a substance by 1 degree Celsius (or 1 Kelvin).\n*   **Units:** Typically expressed in Joules per gram per degree Celsius (J/g\u00b0C) or Joules per kilogram per Kelvin (J/kg\u00b7K). Sometimes also expressed in calories/g\u00b0C or BTU/lb\u00b7\u00b0F.\n*   **Dependency:** Specific heat is **intensive**, meaning it is a **property of the material itself** and does not depend on the amount of substance.  The specific heat of water is the same whether you have a drop or a liter.\n*   **Formula:**  c = Q / (m * \u0394T), where:\n    *   c = Specific Heat\n    *   Q = Heat Added or Removed\n    *   m = Mass of the substance\n    *   \u0394T = Change in Temperature\n\n**Key Differences Summarized:**\n\n| Feature          | Heat Capacity (C)               | Specific Heat (c)                                |\n|-------------------|------------------------------------|---------------------------------------------------|\n| **Definition**   | Heat to raise temp of *given mass* | Heat to raise temp of *1 gram/kilogram*         |\n| **Dependency**   | Extensive (depends on mass)       | Intensive (independent of mass)                   |\n| **Units**          | J/\u00b0C, J/K                          | J/g\u00b0C, J/kg\u00b7K                                     |\n\n**Relationship:**\n\nHeat capacity (C) is related to specific heat (c) by the following equation:\n\n**C = m * c**\n\nWhere:\n\n*   C = Heat Capacity\n*   m = Mass of the substance\n*   c = Specific Heat\n\n**Analogy:**\n\nThink of it this way:\n\n*   **Specific heat** is like the \"recipe\" for how much heat a particular *ingredient* needs to change temperature.\n*   **Heat capacity** is like the total heat needed for the *entire dish*, taking into account how much of each ingredient you have.\n\n**Example:**\n\nWater has a specific heat of approximately 4.184 J/g\u00b0C. This means it takes 4.184 Joules of energy to raise the temperature of 1 gram of water by 1 degree Celsius.\n\nIf you have 100 grams of water, its heat capacity would be:\n\nC = m * c = 100 g * 4.184 J/g\u00b0C = 418.4 J/\u00b0C\n\nThis means it takes 418.4 Joules of energy to raise the temperature of that 100 grams of water by 1 degree Celsius.\n\nIn conclusion, specific heat is a property of the material and heat capacity considers the amount of material you have.\n",
